<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Succession Planting Changes What “Best Seed Company” Means</h2>

  <p>
    A normal seed company article can focus on variety quality alone. Succession planting is different.
  </p>

  <p>
    You need a company that helps with all three of these:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>fast or repeatable crop selection</li>
    <li>clear maturity timelines</li>
    <li>planning support for staggered sowings</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If a catalog has good seed but weak timing information, succession planting becomes guesswork.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Johnny’s Selected Seeds Is the Strongest Overall Pick</h2>

  <p>
    Johnny’s stands out because it does more than list seeds. It supports the planning side of succession planting in a way most catalogs do not.
  </p>

  <p>
    That matters because succession planting is rarely limited by seed availability. It is usually limited by timing mistakes:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>sowing too much at once</li>
    <li>leaving too much time between plantings</li>
    <li>choosing varieties that mature too similarly</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A company that helps you avoid those mistakes is much more useful than a company that simply sells more options.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why West Coast Seeds Is a Strong Home-Garden Pick</h2>

  <p>
    West Coast Seeds works especially well for gardeners who want practical guidance tied closely to real garden use, especially for repeated sowings of quick crops.
  </p>

  <p>
    Its strength is not just the seed list. It is that the catalog and educational content tend to reinforce the idea of timed replanting, shorter harvest windows, and crop turnover in a way that home gardeners can actually apply.
  </p>

  <p>
    For gardeners who are trying to get better at simple successions like lettuce, radishes, spinach, beets, or bush beans, that is useful.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Territorial Seed Makes Sense for Succession Gardeners</h2>

  <p>
    Territorial Seed is a strong fit when succession planting overlaps with season extension and harvest planning.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is important because succession planting is not only about sowing every two weeks in midsummer. It is also about knowing what can follow what:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>what can go in after spring crops finish</li>
    <li>what still matures for fall</li>
    <li>what can be staggered across a longer season</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Territorial tends to fit well for gardeners thinking beyond a single repeat crop and into full-bed turnover.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What the Best Seed Companies for Succession Planting Have in Common</h2>

  <h3>They Have Lots of Fast Crops — But Not Only Fast Crops</h3>
  <p>
    Good succession planting uses both approaches:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>repeating the same fast crop</li>
    <li>mixing crops with different maturity timelines</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A good catalog supports both.
  </p>

  <h3>They Make Maturity Differences Easy to Compare</h3>
  <p>
    If all the lettuces, carrots, or beans look similar in the catalog, it is harder to build intentional harvest spacing.
  </p>

  <h3>They Support Planning, Not Just Purchasing</h3>
  <p>
    This is the biggest separator. Some companies help you think like a planner. Others only help you think like a shopper.
  </p>
</section>

